<bibRefCitation author="Rutzler, K. &amp; Piantoni, C. &amp; Van Soest, R. W. M. &amp; Diaz, M. C." pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 129" refId="ref80693" refString="Rutzler, K., Piantoni, C., Van Soest, R. W. M. &amp; Diaz, M. C. (2014) Diversity of sponges (Porifera) from cryptic habitats on the Belize barrier reef near Carrie Bow Cay. Zootaxa, 3805 (1), 1 - 129. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3805.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Rützler 
<emphasis box="[200,256,1574,1600]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
), and in the SGoM (
<bibRefCitation author="Ugalde, D. &amp; Gomez, P. &amp; Simoes, N." box="[548,761,1574,1601]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="151 - 183" refId="ref82484" refString="Ugalde, D., Gomez, P. &amp; Simoes, N. (2015) Marine sponges (Porifera: Demospongiae) from the Gulf of Mexico, new records and redescription of Erylus trisphaerus (de Laubenfels, 1953). Zootaxa, 3911 (2), 151 - 183. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3911.2.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Ugalde 
<emphasis box="[638,694,1574,1600]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). Furthermore, Carballo 
<emphasis box="[1037,1093,1574,1600]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">et al.</emphasis>
(2004) recorded the species in the Tropical Mexican Pacific. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ugalde, D. &amp; Gomez, P. &amp; Simoes, N." box="[486,709,1610,1637]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="151 - 183" refId="ref82484" refString="Ugalde, D., Gomez, P. &amp; Simoes, N. (2015) Marine sponges (Porifera: Demospongiae) from the Gulf of Mexico, new records and redescription of Erylus trisphaerus (de Laubenfels, 1953). Zootaxa, 3911 (2), 151 - 183. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3911.2.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Ugalde 
<emphasis box="[573,629,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
have questioned this record due to differences in the morphology of spines of spiraster, and tylostyles in loose tracts.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,1502,2033]" lastBlockId="26.[151,1436,151,249]" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
Our material was also collected in coral reefs in the Campeche Bank (see above in material examined), and its spiculation, as well as spicule measurements, fit 
<bibRefCitation author="Ugalde, D. &amp; Gomez, P. &amp; Simoes, N." box="[711,962,1718,1745]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="151 - 183" refId="ref82484" refString="Ugalde, D., Gomez, P. &amp; Simoes, N. (2015) Marine sponges (Porifera: Demospongiae) from the Gulf of Mexico, new records and redescription of Erylus trisphaerus (de Laubenfels, 1953). Zootaxa, 3911 (2), 151 - 183. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3911.2.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Ugalde’s 
<emphasis box="[820,871,1718,1744]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">et al</emphasis>
. (2015)
</bibRefCitation>
material. These authors have described a specimen with orange color 
<emphasis box="[463,538,1755,1780]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">in vivo</emphasis>
and faded-yellow color in ethanol, tylostyles 190–420/7–13 µm (tyle 7.8–13/10– 15 µm), and spirasters (could be split into two categories) 7.8–50.7/1.5–2.6 µm with 1–4 bends. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ugalde, D. &amp; Gomez, P. &amp; Simoes, N." box="[1214,1436,1790,1817]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="151 - 183" refId="ref82484" refString="Ugalde, D., Gomez, P. &amp; Simoes, N. (2015) Marine sponges (Porifera: Demospongiae) from the Gulf of Mexico, new records and redescription of Erylus trisphaerus (de Laubenfels, 1953). Zootaxa, 3911 (2), 151 - 183. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3911.2.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Ugalde 
<emphasis box="[1301,1356,1790,1816]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
have mentioned that the tylostyle’s tyle is predominantly spherical, although the oval shape occurs. In our material tylostyles have predominantly oval tyles, which agrees with specimens from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Rutzler 1974)" baseAuthorityName="Rutzler" baseAuthorityYear="1974" box="[1019,1296,1862,1888]" class="Demospongiae" family="Chondropsidae" genus="Strongylacidon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="bermuda">
Bermuda (
<bibRefCitation author="Rutzler, K." box="[1136,1288,1862,1888]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="32" refId="ref80398" refString="Rutzler, K. (1974) The Burrowing Sponges of Bermuda. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 165, 32. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.165" type="journal article" year="1974">Rützler 1974</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. This author described tylostyles with droplet or elongate tyles (3.7–17.8 µm). Further, he described the species’ color as yellow-brown, its tylostyles with 178–409.4/0.7–11.1 µm and spirasters (some of them called amphiasters―smallest forms) with 14.4–65.6/0.5–3.2 µm and 1–5 bends. The spiculation of the specimens examined here fits 
<bibRefCitation author="Rutzler, K." pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="32" refId="ref80398" refString="Rutzler, K. (1974) The Burrowing Sponges of Bermuda. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 165, 32. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.165" type="journal article" year="1974">Rützler’s (1974)</bibRefCitation>
material too. Tylostyles in our materials are 205–415/5.2–10.4 µm (tyle with 7.8–13 µm) in dimensions. 
<taxonomicName class="Demospongiae" family="Agelasidae" genus="Agelas" kingdom="Animalia" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="27" order="Agelasida" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="minor">A minor</taxonomicName>
point of distinction relates to the smaller spirasters (with up to 7 bends) found by us 19.2–40.3/1–1.2 µm. On the other hand, our material’s yellow color 
<emphasis box="[684,761,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">in vivo</emphasis>
fits better the color reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rutzler, K." box="[1129,1294,187,213]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" pagination="32" refId="ref80398" refString="Rutzler, K. (1974) The Burrowing Sponges of Bermuda. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 165, 32. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.165" type="journal article" year="1974">Rützler (1974)</bibRefCitation>
than that by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ugalde, D. &amp; Gomez, P. &amp; Simoes, N." box="[151,380,222,249]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" pagination="151 - 183" refId="ref82484" refString="Ugalde, D., Gomez, P. &amp; Simoes, N. (2015) Marine sponges (Porifera: Demospongiae) from the Gulf of Mexico, new records and redescription of Erylus trisphaerus (de Laubenfels, 1953). Zootaxa, 3911 (2), 151 - 183. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3911.2.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Ugalde 
<emphasis box="[239,288,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">et al</emphasis>
. (2015)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
